XPO Logistics terminal XDM experienced a UN1805 Low pH Presoak release from a 15-gallon poly drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-quart of product released to a 3’ x 3’ area of the trailer floor/pallet due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents and soda ash solution were deployed and worked into the impacted area to clean and neutralize the release. The impacted absorbents and pallet wood were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum of the product was patched with chem tape and placed into a separate 55- gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

The driver stopped within the first hour to do a load and vehicle check and when opening the trailer to check the load she noticed the pallet and floor looked wet. The driver then called our emergency number and a team was dispatched to the location. The response team found that the lid and ring were no longer seated to the top of the drum and liquid had spilled over the top of the drum. The team then rescued the lid to the drum and cleaned up the material with absorbents and disposed of them in accordance with the regulations. First notification 1427CT Response team arrived 1600CT Clean up was complete 1800CT 1-2 Gallons was released all was contained inside of the trailer.
column169: It was determined that when the pallet was loaded and set in place the ring caught onto the tote next to it causing the lid to pop off. The team is being retrained on loading and container closure procedures as the ring may not have been completely torqued to specification.

column168: Driver was starting his trip for the day and when doing his Pre-Trip noticed liquid on the floor of the trailer and called our emergency response line. Call was received at around 1115et. A team was dispatched and was in rout at 1230et, They arrived on scene at 1330et and started the process of getting information and dawning the appropriate PPE to begin the clean up. They had to remove several containers to get to the drum which was near the middle of a 53ft trailer. They found the drum and noted that it had a small hole in the side that the material was leaking out. The drum was put into a salvage drum and the material was cleaned up using absorbent materials and then disposed of properly. This was completed at approximately 1800et. The containers that had to be removed to gain excess were then reloaded and secured for shipment at 1900et.

Material was shipped as a non-regulated shipment of petroleum distillates. Once received the material was analyzed by our lab and the flash point of the material was determined to be 138F. The material was determined to be a hazardous waste UN 1268 Petroleum Distillates with a waste code of D001 for ignitibility. The material did ship on a hazardous waste manifest (MT# 0206124145JJK). To rectify the situation, we updated the shipping description and waste codes on the hazardous waste manifest. We relabeled the drums with hazardous waste labels and are managing the waste as hazardous.

column168: Company Fuel Driver was delivering gasoline at store at 09:03am. Company driver had two hoses connected from the trailer belly valves to the underground fuel storage tank (UST), and was in the process of unloading fuel. Cones were in place to protect the area as well as vehicle lights activated for warnings.  A white pickup truck (Super Duty) bearing Maryland registration # 9EC0549, pulling a cement mixer trailer, disregarded the activated lights and orange security cones of our vehicle; and drove over the hose fitting connected to the UST and tore the delivery hose coupler and the lip off the UST, subsequently releasing approximately 20 gallons of gasoline onto the pavement.  VA State Police (Trooper J.B. Moore) was notified, arrived at the location of the "hit and run" regarding the pickup truck. Fuel driver captured a photo of the truck license plate that ran over the fitting and hose and provided plate # to Law Enforcement. Material spilled was contained by the fuel driver using absorbent pads, and emptied the remaining fuel in the hose into the UST. No fuel contaminated the ground nor entered into any water systems.
column169: No recommendations for improvement to prevent this incident as our driver had properly secured the scene prior to delivery, had warning lights active and was attentive to his surroundings

column168: Unsecured freight

On February 15, 2204, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN1219 had a faulty cap during transit and released approximately 165-gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted surface and worked them in with hand tools. A forklift provided by RLC was used to gravity transfer the remaining product from the one (1) damaged 330-gallon tote into one (1) new 330-gallon tote. Absorbent pads and cleaners were used to remove all residual product from the impacted surfaces. All UN1219-impacted materials were collected and containerized into one (1) 5-gallon pail for disposal purposes.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XKC experienced a release UN3266 Mainline Liquid 102 from a 250-gallon poly tote. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 10-gallons of material released to a 12’ x 2’ area of the trailer floor and a 10’ x 10’ area of the concrete lot underneath the trailer due to a pinhole puncture. The material was transferred from the damaged tote into a new one. Citric acid solution and absorbents were then deployed and worked into the impacted areas to clean and neutralize the release. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized along with all spent absorbents into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On February 10, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of UN1760 was damaged due to unknown causes and released approximately seven (7) gallons of product to the trailer floor, lift gate, wood, and asphalt ground. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Restoration, LLC (ER) to remediate the impacted site.  Crews deployed granular absorbents to the impacted areas and worked them in with hand tools. A hose was utilized to perform a gravity transfer to remove the remaining product from the damaged tote into a new tote provided by ER. The new tote was properly labeled and left on-site for disposal. Crews dismantled the damaged tote and impacted wooden pallet with hand tools for disposal purposes. All spent absorbents, impacted pallet, and tote were collected and containerized into five (5) 55-gallon drums for disposal.

On 2/12/2024, I john Vergis Hazardous Materials Officer for the WLE, was called by the WLE Car Shop Manager @0730 hrs. about tank car UTLX 205661 leaking in the WLE Rook Yard.  When I arrived to look at the car, I could see that is was leaking product from the protective housing on top the car.  I got on top the car and removed seal number 451443 from the protective housing cover and noticed that product was leaking from the Sample Line Valve.   Product was leaking from the valve plug.  I checked to see of the valve handle was shut and it was not tight.  I turned the valve handle one complete turn before it was shut tight.  I then checked to see if the valve plug was loose and when I touched the plug, it fell out.  I installed new thread sealant on the plug and installed it in the valve and tightened it tool tight.  I then cleaned off the top and sides of the car the best I could.  I installed new seal number 0000225 on the protective housing lid and then released the car back into transportation.

column168: On 02/01/2024, at 0900 hours, personnel in the CSXT Collinwood Yard discovered MJEX 73527, a loaded tank car of Methyl Isobutyl Carbinol, leaking from the manway area.  The car was isolated and The Shipper, Altivia, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report 2024-0201-00063). EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the product leaking from the liquid line valve mounting flange as a result of the mounting flange bolts being less than tool tight. Contractor personnel tightened the flange bolts to stop the release. The issue identified and corrective action were communicated to the shipper’s representative (Timothy Albert, 740-533-5200). The car was held out of transportation pending further repair/qualification by a certified mobile repair unit or One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from FRA.
